08352nam a22008175i 9780804778923DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222002cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047789237 a10.1515/97808047789232doi  a(DE-B1597)581541  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPOL0060002bisacsh00aParty, Process, and Political Change in Congress, Volume 1 :bNew Perspectives on the History of Congress /ced. by David W. Brady, Mathew D. McCubbins. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (576 p.) :b78 tables, 67 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSocial Science History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tContributors -- tTables -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Party, Process, and Political Change: New Perspectives on the History of Congress -- tPart I Parties, Committees, and Political Change in Congress -- t2. The Historical Variability in Conditional Party Government, 1877–1994 -- t3. Do Parties Matter? -- t4. Party and Preference in Congressional Decision Making: Roll Call Voting in the House of Representatives, 1889–1999 -- t5. Agenda Power in the U.S. House of Representatives, 1877–1986 -- t6. Agenda Power in the U.S. Senate, 1877–1986 -- t7. Party Loyalty and Committee Leadership in the House, 1921– 40 -- tPart II The Evolution and Choice of Congressional Institutions -- t8. Order from Chaos: The Transformation of the Committee System in the House, 1816 –22 -- t9. Leadership and Institutional Change in the Nineteenth- Century House -- t10. Institutional Evolution and the Rise of the Tuesday-Thursday Club in the House of Representatives -- t11. Policy Leadership and the Development of the Modern Senate -- tPart III Policy Choice and Congressional Institutions -- t12. Why Congress? What the Failure of the Confederation Congress and the Survival of the Federal Congress Tell Us About the New Institutionalism -- t13. Agenda Manipulation, Strategic Voting, and Legislative Details in the Compromise of 1850 -- t14. Congress and the Territorial Expansion of the United States -- t15. Representation of the Antebellum South in the House of Representatives: Measuring the Impact of the Three-Fifths Clause -- tAfterword: History as a Laboratory -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tName Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent decades, political scientists have produced an enormous body of scholarship dealing with the U.S. Congress, and in particular congressional organization. However, most of this research has focused on Congress in the twentieth century—especially the post-New Deal era—and the long history of Congress has been largely neglected. The contributors to this book demonstrate that this inattention to congressional history has denied us many rich opportunities to more fully understand the evolution and functioning of the modern Congress. In striking contrast to the modern era, which is marked by only modest partisan realignment and institutional change, the period preceding the New Deal was a time of rapid and substantial change in Congress. During the nation’s first 150 years, parties emerged, developed, and realigned; the standing rules of the House and Senate expanded and underwent profound changes; the workload of Congress increased dramatically; and both houses grew considerably in size. Studying history is valuable in large part because it allows scholars to observe greater variation in many of the parameters of their theories, and to test their core assumptions. A historical approach pushes scholars to recognize and confront the limits of their theories, resulting in theories that have increased validity and broader applicability. Thus, incorporating history into political science gives us a more dynamic view of Congress than the relatively static picture that emerges from a strict focus on recent periods. Each contributor engages one of three general questions that have animated the literature on congressional politics in recent years: What is the role of party organizations in policy making? In what ways have congressional process and procedure changed over the years? How does congressional process and procedure affect congressional politics and policy?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aHistory -- Political. 4aPolitics -- United States. 4aSociology -- Social Movements, Civil Society, and Politics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Legislative Branch.2bisacsh1 aAldrich, John H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Mark M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrady, David W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrady, David W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCampbell, Andrea C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, Gary W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinegold, Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFink, Evelyn C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGamm, Gerald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHumes, Brian D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenkins, Jeffery A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJillson, Calvin C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCubbins, Mathew D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMccarty, Nolan, econtributor.4ctb4h